```suggestion
/-- 
Given a finset of elements `  `, extract all the elements of the form ``. This
forms a quasi-inverse to `disjSum`, in that it recovers its left input.
-/
```

```suggestion
/-- 
Given a finset of elements `  `, extract all the elements of the form ``. This
forms a quasi-inverse to `disjSum`, in that it recovers its right input.
-/
```
`@[simp]`?
sure, why not
Do we have the `Option` version of this? If so, a docstring reference would be good.
Loogle can't find it, so I don't think so
`List.reduceOption` is what I'm thinking of.
There's also List.partitionMap which is a closer analogy, but it has basically no API, in particular not nearly enough to show you get something well-defined on multisets
Nice find. Can you leave a note somewhere in this file about that function? No need to write any new theorems in this PR, but I think `s.toLeft` is morally `(partitionMap id s).1`?
Morally it is - indeed my first attempt at this definition was in terms of that, but it's way more painful to use in context. Will add a comment
The point here is that this is a computable version of `Finset.preimage .inl`, right?
Sure - I don't think of it like that but it's a valid way of viewing it! I can't add that lemma here because importing preimage would make an import cycle
Added it to Preimage.lean instead

```suggestion
@[simp] lemma toLeft_disjSum : (s.disjSum t).toLeft = s := by ext x; simp
```
(and throughout)
Do we have `Sum.swap`? If so, it would be good to show that `(s.map swap).toLeft = s.toRight` and vice versa.
We have it as a map but not as an embedding, so I added the `.image` version of this.
We have it as the Equiv, so I think you can get the `map` version from that.
Added
Can you add the `cons` version of these too?
Done
These shouldn't need `DecidableEq`
